   â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
   Title: Dynamic Context-Adaptive Multilingual Math Reasoning Framework
   Abstract: This paper introduces a conceptual innovation in small language models (SLMs) by reframing short-context reasoning as a dynamic, multilingual math problem-solving process. We propose a framework that unifies contextual filtering with cross-lingual mathematical knowledge retrieval, enabling SLMs to perform precise, chain-of-thought reasoning across languages with minimal input. By using adaptive embeddings and retrieval-enhanced prompts, our system dynamically aligns with the most relevant knowledge, transforming the way SLMs approach math reasoning from a static, input-limited task to an interactive, self-adjusting process. Our results demonstrate that this approach significantly enhances accuracy and fluency in multilingual math reasoning tasks, maintaining efficiency without increasing model size or context length.
   Problem Framing: Reframe short-context reasoning in small language models from a limitation to a strategic, adaptive process that dynamically integrates multilingual mathematical knowledge. The challenge lies in enabling SLMs to perform accurate and fluent reasoning in a multilingual setting, where both linguistic diversity and input constraints require a modular yet context-aware system. Traditional methods either treat math reasoning and context handling as separate, or apply static encodings that fail to adapt to the evolving nature of reasoning across languages and domains.
   Gap Pattern: Existing approaches to short-context reasoning in small language models primarily focus on static processing of input, failing to recognize the opportunity to dynamically realign the reasoning process with multilingual mathematical knowledge. Current retrieval-augmented methods do not unify the filtering of irrelevant context with the retrieval of domain-specific knowledge, leading to suboptimal performance in cross-lingual math reasoning tasks. This disconnect prevents SLMs from actively shaping their reasoning strategies in response to linguistic and mathematical cues, limiting their generalization and precision.
   Solution: We transform the way small language models perform short-context reasoning by unifying it with cross-lingual mathematical knowledge retrieval in a dynamically adaptive framework. Our approach enables the model to not only filter noisy or irrelevant information in real-time but also to guide retrieval mechanisms based on the filtered context, ensuring that only the most relevant multilingual math knowledge is accessed. This is achieved through adaptive embeddings that bridge linguistic and mathematical domains, a self-modulating reasoning architecture that co-evolves during inference, and constrained yet effective interaction protocols that optimize information flow and retrieval precision. The result is a system that reframes short context not as a barrier but as a catalyst for focused, linguistically and mathematically aligned reasoning.
   Method: Implement a Semi-Markov CRF-based filtering mechanism during decoding to dynamically prune irrelevant input segments; Integrate FiD-Light as a retrieval module that optimizes encoder-decoder information flow and introduces re-ranking for provenance precision; Deploy a Contextualized Generative Retrieval model that uses contextualized embeddings as vocabulary embeddings during decoding, enabling adaptive cross-lingual knowledge retrieval and alignment with mathematical concepts.
   Claims:
     1. Transform short-context reasoning in small language models from a static input constraint to a dynamic, multilingual math knowledge alignment process by integrating adaptive filtering with cross-lingual retrieval mechanisms.
     2. Reframe the role of contextualized embeddings from a passive representation tool to an active participant in the retrieval process, enabling the model to dynamically source and align with relevant mathematical knowledge across languages.
     3. Transform retrieval-augmented math reasoning into a self-modulating, context-driven system that co-evolves its structure and function during inference, allowing SLMs to shape their reasoning strategy in real-time based on linguistic cues and mathematical requirements.
