   â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
   Title: Transforming Short-Context Reasoning in Small Language Models through Conceptual Self-Evolution and Contextualized Code Infilling
   Abstract: This paper transforms short-context mathematical reasoning in small language models (SLMs) into a concept-level self-evolving process by reframing it as a dynamic, context-aware code infilling task, where knowledge is iteratively refined and aligned across languages. We employ CodeT5 as a foundational model and integrate static analysis to guide the evolution of symbolic reasoning paths and contextualized embeddings during decoding. This conceptual innovation enables SLMs to engage in continuous, interactive reasoning refinement in multilingual, knowledge-intensive settings, without reliance on external training or static augmentation.
   Problem Framing: Short-context reasoning in small language models is reframed from a mere input limitation problem to a conceptual misalignment between static knowledge representations and the need for dynamic, self-evolving symbolic planning. Traditional models treat mathematical inference as a fixed rule application or isolated retrieval task, failing to adapt reasoning strategies in real-time to linguistic and mathematical context signals. The challenge lies in creating a unified framework where reasoning and knowledge access co-evolve based on contextual feedback, enabling SLMs to dynamically resolve ambiguity and maintain conceptual consistency across languages.
   Gap Pattern: Existing approaches to short-context reasoning in SLMs treat retrieval and reasoning as modular or static processes, often relying on post-hoc augmentation or disjointed prompting strategies. These methods lack the conceptual foundation for continuous refinement of symbolic knowledge in response to context and feedback. While techniques such as retrieval-augmented generation, dynamic knowledge filtering, and interactive debugging have been explored, they are not unified under a single conceptual evolution paradigm that allows SLMs to actively transform their knowledge access and reasoning paths based on evolving internal states and multilingual constraints.
   Solution: We transform short-context reasoning in SLMs into a concept-level self-evolving symbolic knowledge-flow process by reframing it as a dynamic code infilling task. This approach enables the model to iteratively refine its understanding of mathematical concepts through context-aware embeddings and static analysis. By integrating CodeT5 with a planning-driven Semi-Markov CRF, we create a system where reasoning segments are dynamically filtered and aligned with linguistic and mathematical signals. A dual re-ranking mechanism ensures that retrieved knowledge is contextually and conceptually coherent. This novel paradigm shifts the focus from static augmentation to active, interactive knowledge refinement, enabling SLMs to adapt their reasoning strategies in real-time, especially in multilingual and sparse knowledge environments.
   Method: Reframe mathematical reasoning as code infilling with CodeT5 and static analysis to generate dynamic contexts; Introduce a planning-driven Semi-Markov CRF with a novel filtering mechanism that dynamically segments and eliminates irrelevant reasoning subtasks during decoding; Deploy a Contextualized Generative Retrieval model using evolving contextualized embeddings as vocab embeddings, integrated with a dual re-ranking system balancing linguistic and mathematical signals for precise knowledge alignment.
   Claims:
     1. We transform short-context mathematical reasoning from a static, input-limited problem to a dynamic, concept-level self-evolving symbolic knowledge-flow by reframing it as a code infilling task with CodeT5 and static analysis, enabling real-time refinement of reasoning paths and contextualized embeddings.
     2. We reframe cross-lingual knowledge alignment and retrieval as an iterative, context-sensitive process that actively evolves during decoding, leveraging a dual re-ranking mechanism that merges linguistic and mathematical coherence into a unified conceptual refinement loop.
     3. We transform the traditional separation of reasoning and retrieval into a co-evolving, planning-based symbolic framework by introducing a dynamic segmentation filter in the Semi-Markov CRF, ensuring that knowledge access and reasoning strategy are mutually reinforcing and conceptually grounded.
